INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '160aa1d1-1f9a-4a1a-a39e-138b5cf2faef',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Prometheus Metrics Design — Naming, Cardinality, and Choosing the Right Type$escape$,
  $escape$Prometheus metric names must follow `<namespace>_<subsystem>_<unit>_total` for counters and include base units (seconds, bytes) — never milliseconds. `http_request_duration_seconds` is canonical; `requestLatencyMs` will cause alerts to silently drift.

Cardinality explosion kills Prometheus. Every unique label combination creates a new time series. A `user_id` label on a high-traffic metric can push you past 10M series and OOM your TSDB. Use `prometheus_tsdb_head_series` to monitor growth. Reserve labels for low-cardinality dimensions: `method`, `status_code`, `route` — never emails, UUIDs, or raw URLs.

Type discipline matters at query time. Use `counter` for monotonically increasing values (`requests_total`, `errors_total`) and always wrap with `rate()` or `increase()`. Use `gauge` for values that go up and down (`goroutines_active`, `queue_depth`). Use `histogram` — not `summary` — when you need quantiles across multiple instances, since `histogram_quantile()` is aggregatable across replicas; `summary` quantiles are computed client-side and cannot be aggregated in PromQL.$escape$,
  $escape$# Good: namespaced, unit-suffixed, low-cardinality labels
http_request_duration_seconds_bucket{method="POST", route="/api/bytes", status_code="200"}

# Bad: high-cardinality label
http_requests_total{user_id="uuid-abc-123"}  # Never do this

# PromQL: aggregatable quantile from histogram (works across replicas)
histogram_quantile(0.99,
  sum by (le, route) (
    rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket[5m])
  )
)

# Monitor your own cardinality
prometheus_tsdb_head_series > 500000$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
