INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '586cfde5-7dfa-4700-9310-b07599a993bc',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Prometheus Dashboards — RED and USE Methods Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$RED and USE are complementary lenses on your system. RED (Rate, Errors, Duration) targets request-driven services; USE (Utilization, Saturation, Errors) targets resources like CPU, memory, and disk.

For RED in Prometheus, derive all three from a single `http_request_duration_seconds` histogram. Rate comes from `rate()` on the `_count` suffix, errors from filtering `{status=~"5.."}`, and duration (p99) from `histogram_quantile(0.99, ...)` on the `_bucket` suffix.

For USE, Prometheus exposes resource metrics via `node_exporter`. Utilization is `rate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode!="idle"}[5m])`, saturation is `node_load1` vs CPU count, and errors are `node_disk_io_time_seconds_total` or ECC memory counters.

The key mistake is mixing methods — don't apply USE to HTTP services or RED to raw resources. Pin each panel to its correct method. Group RED panels by service label, USE panels by instance. Use `recording rules` to pre-compute expensive `histogram_quantile` calls so dashboards load fast under high cardinality.$escape$,
  $escape$# RED — request rate, error rate, p99 latency
sum(rate(http_request_duration_seconds_count{job="api"}[5m])) by (route)

sum(rate(http_request_duration_seconds_count{job="api",status=~"5.."}[5m])) by (route)

histogram_quantile(0.99,
  sum(rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket{job="api"}[5m])) by (le, route)
)

# USE — CPU utilization, saturation, errors
1 - avg(rate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) by (instance)

node_load1 / count(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}) by (instance)

rate(node_disk_io_time_seconds_total[5m])$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
