INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '55c0491a-5d3d-46cc-9f7f-31c078302a9f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Prometheus + Pyroscope — Continuous Profiling and Flame Graphs in Production$escape$,
  $escape$Prometheus metrics tell you *that* CPU is spiking — continuous profiling tells you *why*. Grafana Pyroscope, the continuous profiling backend in the Prometheus/Grafana stack, uses the same `job`/`instance` label model, enabling direct correlation between `rate(process_cpu_seconds_total[1m])` spikes and flame graphs.

When profiles are pushed with labels matching your Prometheus targets, Grafana's **Explore Profiles** view lets you jump from a firing alert into a flame graph scoped to the exact time window. The flame graph aggregates sampled stack traces across the push interval, surfacing CPU hotspots, memory allocation pressure, and goroutine contention — context that `go_goroutines` and `process_cpu_seconds_total` can signal but never localize.

In Go services, the `pyroscope-go` SDK wraps `runtime/pprof` and streams profiles every 10s by default. Mirror your Prometheus `job` and `instance` labels exactly in `Tags` — Grafana uses these to auto-link metric panels to profiles via the **Link to Pyroscope** datasource setting.

For heap hotspots, enable `ProfileAllocSpace` and `ProfileAllocObjects`. These pinpoint allocation-heavy call paths that `go_memstats_heap_inuse_bytes` can flag but never isolate.$escape$,
  $escape$profiler, _ := pyroscope.Start(pyroscope.Config{
    ApplicationName: "payment-service",
    ServerAddress:   "http://pyroscope:4040",
    // Mirror Prometheus job/instance labels for Grafana auto-linking
    Tags: map[string]string{
        "job":      "payment-service",
        "instance": os.Getenv("HOSTNAME"),
    },
    ProfileTypes: []pyroscope.ProfileType{
        pyroscope.ProfileCPU,
        pyroscope.ProfileAllocObjects,
        pyroscope.ProfileAllocSpace,
        pyroscope.ProfileGoroutines,
    },
})
defer profiler.Stop()$escape$,
  $escape$go$escape$,
